## The Cleaner Method

Typing out the bulky `for` loop every time is annoying. JavaScript gives arrays a much cleaner method called **`.forEach()`**.

It takes an Arrow Function *inside* of it, and runs that function once for every item in the array.

```javascript
let colors = ["Red", "Blue", "Green"];

// For each item in the array, call it 'color', and run this code!
colors.forEach( (color) => {
  console.log("I love the color " + color);
});
```

This is much cleaner! You don't have to track `i` or check `.length`.

## Creating New Arrays

What if you don't just want to print things out, but want to magically transform an array into a brand new array?

Use **`.map()`**! It works EXACTLY like `.forEach()`, but its specific job is to build and output a completely fresh array based on your instructions.

```javascript
let lowPrices = [1, 2, 3];

// Make a NEW array where everything is multiplied pointlessly by 10!
let highPrices = lowPrices.map( (price) => {
  return price * 10;
});

console.log(highPrices); // [10, 20, 30]
```

`.map()` is immensely popular in React and modern UI development!
